    <text>
        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 16. <placeName type="findspot"
                    >Rathglass</placeName></name>, Co. <placeName type="county"
                >Carlow</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                        target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CW013-018001-"
                        >CW013-018001-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Standing stone pair</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Standing in a field, on an east-west aligned low ridge. </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>1 of a pair of coarse-grained granite stones standing 3m apart.
                        Ogham-inscribed stone to the east tapers to a point <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >19</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. W stone: <rs type="material"/>
                        <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.5</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.8</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth"
                        >0.5</measure>m</rs>; E (Ogham) stone: <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.3</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.62</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth"
                            >0.82</measure>m</rs>. Chocking stones of both sockets exposed <ref
                            type="bibliog" target="#BRA1993">(<bibl><author>Brindley</author> and
                                    <author>Kilfeather</author>
                                <date when="1993">1993</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >14</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p>
                    
                </div>

                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>On 2 angles of eastern stone facing its companion, up-up <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >19</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition">
                <head>Transcription</head>
                <ab>
                    <lb/>
                    <persName><w lemma="DUNAIDONAS"> DUNAIDONAS/ </w></persName>
                    <w type="formula" lemma="MAQI">MAQI</w>
                    <persName><w lemma="MARIANI"> MARIANI </w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p><q>of <persName xml:lang="ga">Donnáed</persName> son of <persName xml:lang="la"
                            >Marianus</persName></q></p>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                    <ab>
                        <ref target="http://www.megalithomania.com/show/site/326"
                            >http://www.megalithomania.com/show/site/326</ref>
                    </ab>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                    <ab>
                        <name type="author">Macalister</name><ptr type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                        />: <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/archaeology/cisp/database/picpage/rglas_1_1.html"
                            >http://www.ucl.ac.uk/archaeology/cisp/database/picpage/rglas_1_1.html</ref>
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">                    
                    <item n="1"><p> The personal name DUNAIDONAS contains the elements
                        DUN(A)- (probably <hi rend="italic">don(n)</hi> 'dun, brown'; cf. DOVAIDONA[S], <foreign xml:lang="ga"><hi rend="italic">Dubáed</hi></foreign> with <hi rend="italic">dub</hi> 'black') and one of the most frequently occurring elements in final
                        position, -AIDONAS (<hi rend="italic">áed</hi> 'fire'), with the composition vowel 'a' elided before the initial vowel of -AIDONAS <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991"
                            >(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">103,
                                    117</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p>MARIANI is an example of a genitive form of a Latin name, <persName xml:lang="la">Marianus</persName>,
                        also found on <ref
                            target="search.php?ciic=188"
                            >CIIC 188</ref>
                                    <placeName type="findspot">Kinard East</placeName>,
                                Co. <placeName type="county">Kerry</placeName> <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                    <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >113</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                    <item n="3"><p> Both of these namse display pre-apocope
                        endings suggesting that the inscription is <origDate notBefore="0400" notAfter="0500">pre 6th century</origDate> (<ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991"
                            ><bibl><author>McManus</author>
                            <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">103,
                                116</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Standing stones 3m apart on an east-west aligned ridge in
                            townland of <placeName type="findspot">Rathglass</placeName> and barony
                            of <placeName type="barony">Rathvilly</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-6.720154, 52.784779</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location probably original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">On find site (<date when="2010-03-26"
                            >26/3/10</date>: Ogham stone fallen over in bad weather. Re-visit <date when="2017-03-26"
                                >26/3/17</date>: Ogham stone re-erected by farmer). The present
                            location of this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CW013-018001-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>Recording</head>
                <p>First mentioned in '<title level="m">Irish Independant</title>' <date
                        when="1910-11-26">26th Nov 1910</date> by <name type="author"
                            ><surname>McDonnell</surname>, <forename>P</forename></name>. <ref
                        type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                            <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >19</biblScope></bibl>)</ref></p>
            </div>
